Denique Smith, Netwerk24Richard Smith, the first team rugby coach of Bishops Diocesan College in Cape Town. (Facebook) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - Richard Smith, the first team rugby coach of Bishops Diocesan College, is still in the intensive care unit of the Life Vincent Pallotti Hospital in Cape Town, after burglars stabbed him in the back of the neck with a screwdriver.The burglars broke into his house in Claremont last Tuesday at 02:30, attacked him and tied him up. His wife, Nina, who was sleeping in the baby's room, was also tied up when she went to investigate what was causing the noise in their bedroom, Netwerk24 reported.Smith&rsquo;s sister, Debi Greybe, says his condition remains unchanged."We are still in shock that my brother was the victim of such a gruesome act of violence. The support we have received from family and friends from across the world and in the community, is proof of the type of person he is.""Richard touched so many people with his positivity, selflessness, loyalty, devotion and unconditional love for his wife, children, family, friends and acquaintances. He always gives something to others."The family looks forward to showing him the messages that have been streaming in from all over.Nick Maurer, Nina&rsquo;s brother, said last week that the robbers also held the couple&rsquo;s children, their infant son Sebastian and six-year-old daughter Lara captive in the main bedroom.After the robbers fled, Nina phoned to get help. The robbers fled with the couple&rsquo;s cellphones, laptops and wallets.No arrests have been made, police spokesperson Captain FC van Wyk said. Anyone with information can phone Constable Mkhuseli Ngqiyana at 021 658 2266. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.